WEBVTT

00:42.146 --> 00:47.414
Matthew 19, if you have your Bibles open there to Matthew 19, I'm gonna be reading verses 16 through 22.

00:47.514 --> 00:50.739
It's a short story, might be familiar to many of you.

00:50.779 --> 00:56.047
And after I read it, we'll pray and we'll dig out this text together today.

00:56.147 --> 01:08.466
So Matthew 19 starting in verse 16 says, now behold, one came and said to him, that is Jesus, good teacher, what good thing shall I do that I may have eternal life?

01:08.866 --> 01:12.191
And so he said, Jesus said to him, why do you call me good?

01:12.852 --> 01:14.655
No one is good, but one, that is God.

01:15.356 --> 01:18.801
But if you want to enter into life, keep the commandments.

01:18.821 --> 01:20.283
And he said to him, which ones?

01:20.884 --> 01:22.406
And Jesus said, you shall not murder.

01:22.787 --> 01:24.109
You shall not commit adultery.

01:24.410 --> 01:25.451
You shall not steal.

01:25.892 --> 01:27.534
You shall not bear false witness.

01:27.955 --> 01:29.297
Honor your father and mother.

01:29.677 --> 01:31.841
And you shall love your neighbor as yourself.

01:32.502 --> 01:36.047
And the young man said to him, all these things I have kept from my youth.

01:36.608 --> 01:37.970
What do I still lack?

01:38.306 --> 01:46.515
And Jesus said to him, if you want to be perfect, go sell what you have and give to the poor and you will have treasure in heaven and come follow me.

01:47.537 --> 01:53.804
But when the young man heard that saying, he went away sorrowful for he had great possessions.

01:54.284 --> 01:55.285
Let's pause there and pray.

01:56.787 --> 02:01.633
Father in heaven, we commit our Bible study to you now, Lord, that you would use your word to speak to our hearts today.

02:02.233 --> 02:06.258
We're grateful for your love and your mercy in our lives and we pray that you would

02:06.562 --> 02:12.273
reveal exactly what you want each of us to see and hear and understand from this passage today.

02:13.094 --> 02:16.461
We give you praise, glory, and honor in Jesus' name.

02:17.302 --> 02:19.106
And everybody said amen.

02:20.688 --> 02:25.177
Well, this guy mentioned here in the story is unnamed in the Bible.

02:25.257 --> 02:25.778
There's

02:25.890 --> 02:27.512
There's no record of his name.

02:27.552 --> 02:31.456
This story is recorded in three out of the four gospels.

02:31.617 --> 02:34.800
Matthew, Mark, and Luke tell us this story.

02:35.241 --> 02:40.587
And between all three of those books, we get a better understanding of a little bit about this guy.

02:41.028 --> 02:44.131
Matthew tells us in particular that he's young.

02:44.291 --> 02:45.593
That's verse 22.

02:46.394 --> 02:53.522
Luke, when he records this story, tells us that he is a ruler, which probably means he is the ruler of a synagogue.

02:53.794 --> 02:59.303
And all three gospels, Matthew, Mark, and Luke, tell us that he is wealthy.

02:59.443 --> 03:01.787
So that's the description of this guy.

03:01.867 --> 03:02.969
He is rich.

03:03.710 --> 03:04.912
He is young.

03:05.473 --> 03:06.915
He is successful.

03:07.476 --> 03:09.619
And he's living in the first century Roman Empire.

03:10.080 --> 03:12.664
So I want you to picture Mark Zuckerberg in a tunic.

03:15.228 --> 03:17.372
Who is squelching your free speech.

03:17.412 --> 03:18.834
But anyway, this is where

03:19.906 --> 03:25.071
This is where we are here in verse 16 and he comes to Jesus and he asks a question.

03:25.151 --> 03:31.377
This is the question, good teacher, what good things shall I do that I may have eternal life.

03:31.497 --> 03:34.280
Now let's give the guy some props first, okay?

03:34.300 --> 03:43.528
Because there's some good qualities about this guy and I wanna point him out with you and the first one is that he is in fact seeking eternal life and that's a good thing.

03:44.109 --> 03:45.630
What exactly is eternal life?

03:46.031 --> 03:49.714
Eternal life is the belief that there is life after death

03:50.050 --> 03:56.361
that the human soul does live on after death, either in heaven or in hell.

03:56.381 --> 03:57.944
That's the idea of eternal life.

03:58.626 --> 04:05.117
And this guy is obviously seeking Jesus because he wants to know how to go to the heaven part of the afterlife.

04:05.538 --> 04:07.642
Nobody needs directions how to get to hell.

04:07.682 --> 04:09.305
We'll get there on our own very well.

04:09.345 --> 04:09.906
Thank you.

04:10.434 --> 04:13.238
But we need some help understanding, well, how do we get to heaven?

04:13.278 --> 04:19.969
And this guy comes to Jesus and he asks this question, how can I have eternal life, the idea after I die, how do I get to heaven?

04:20.429 --> 04:22.452
There are many people in the world like this guy.

04:23.454 --> 04:24.876
They believe that heaven exists.

04:25.938 --> 04:30.985
They hope to get there one day, but they're not sure how or if they will actually get there.

04:31.827 --> 04:39.218
According to a recent CBS news poll, 66% of Americans believe that both heaven and hell exist.

04:39.778 --> 04:44.025
I wish you were 100%, but that's the best that Americans are going to do, I suppose.

04:44.045 --> 04:48.633
66% of Americans believe that both heaven and hell exist.

04:49.074 --> 04:58.129
And among those who believe that both heaven and hell exist, 82% expect to wind up in heaven at the end of their lives.

04:58.149 --> 05:02.035
2% say they expect to end up in hell.

05:03.417 --> 05:06.162
9% don't think they will be in either place.

05:06.850 --> 05:09.214
And if my math is correct, there's still another 7%.

05:09.654 --> 05:11.357
I suppose it didn't have an opinion at all.

05:12.138 --> 05:17.606
But when you look at the numbers here, you got at least love the raw honesty of the 2%.

05:17.787 --> 05:22.414
I mean, the 2% of people are like, yeah, no, I'm going to go to hell for sure.

05:23.315 --> 05:23.856
That's me.

05:23.996 --> 05:25.138
No question about it.

05:25.198 --> 05:26.079
No heaven for me.

05:29.004 --> 05:30.546
I don't celebrate it.

05:30.566 --> 05:33.851
I'm just saying you got at least respect their raw honesty there.

05:33.871 --> 05:35.954
But you have to also be curious

05:36.578 --> 05:37.319
about the 82%.

05:37.399 --> 05:46.410
The 82% of people who really think they're gonna go to heaven, but a lot of whom probably have no idea how to really get there.

05:46.450 --> 05:51.116
They just think, as the survey gave us the answer, that they're gonna end up there.

05:51.136 --> 05:52.597
You don't just end up there.

05:53.078 --> 05:57.643
You have to make a decision, and what is the decision, and how are you able to get there?

05:57.663 --> 06:03.090
Well, if that's you today, if you have questions about that, and you're thinking, you know, I'm part of the 82%,

06:03.426 --> 06:06.049
But I'm not really sure how or if I'm going to make it.

06:06.210 --> 06:14.140
Or if you're part of the 2%, like I don't think I'm going to get there at all, stay tuned because I'll have more to say better than the course of our study together.

06:14.560 --> 06:23.231
But one of the things that I love about this guy in this story is that he asks a question at this particular stage in his life.

06:23.672 --> 06:27.937
And the stage that he is in, Matthew tells us, is he's young.

06:27.977 --> 06:29.719
He's youthful.

06:29.759 --> 06:31.922
That doesn't tell us his age exactly.

06:32.002 --> 06:39.795
But it tells us specifically there in verse 22 and in verse 20 that he is young.

06:40.737 --> 06:44.604
And I find it intriguing because most young people don't think about their own mortality.

06:45.385 --> 06:50.935
Most young people are just living their lives as they want and they don't really think about the reality of death.

06:51.315 --> 06:53.479
But everybody needs to at least think about that.

06:54.481 --> 06:57.586
Everybody needs to understand

06:57.922 --> 06:59.987
that we will all one day die.

07:00.047 --> 07:02.452
Here's a statistic that has proven to be true.

07:02.813 --> 07:04.116
10 out of 10 people die.

07:06.381 --> 07:15.201
Young and old, rich and poor, educated and uneducated, male and female, no gender is spared, no person is exempt, no life is immune.

07:15.682 --> 07:17.266
We all die eventually.

07:17.890 --> 07:21.774
Ecclesiastes 8, 8, the Bible says, no man has power over the day of his death.

07:22.154 --> 07:29.081
And Psalm 89 verse 48 says, what men can live and not see death or save himself from the power of the grave.

07:30.802 --> 07:34.045
The fact of the matter is that nearly two people die every second.

07:34.946 --> 07:37.048
More than 6,000 people an hour.

07:38.129 --> 07:45.816
Roughly 155,000 people die every day and about 57 million people die each year.

07:45.856 --> 07:47.538
No one outruns it.

07:47.874 --> 07:49.957
and no one outmaneuvers it.

07:50.818 --> 07:58.427
The finest surgeon might be able to enhance your life, but he or she cannot eliminate your death.

07:59.889 --> 08:13.485
Pop all the pills you want, eat all the green vegetables you want, stay out of the sun, exercise regularly, and you might improve the quality of your life, but you cannot eliminate the inevitability of your death.

08:14.687 --> 08:15.428
We all die.

08:16.669 --> 08:17.330
And then what?

08:18.306 --> 08:24.152
You need to figure it out because you cannot have a peace in life until you have an answer for death.

08:25.654 --> 08:26.074
That's true.

08:26.394 --> 08:30.158
You cannot have a peace in life until you have an answer for death.

08:30.298 --> 08:32.521
So in our story here, that's where this guy is.

08:33.302 --> 08:41.450
He's young, he's rich, he's successful, but he realizes that all that cannot help him with the question of eternal life.

08:42.571 --> 08:43.933
And so he comes to Jesus here.

08:43.953 --> 08:45.234
And the second thing that I

08:45.474 --> 08:47.036
want to give this guy props for.

08:47.156 --> 08:50.381
Number two is that he is doing a lot of things well.

08:51.443 --> 08:59.394
Jesus is gonna point out some things and he's gonna acknowledge some things and what we learned about him is that he's doing some things well here.

08:59.754 --> 09:13.394
When Jesus answers the guy's question, good teacher, what good thing must I do to inherit eternal life, to have eternal life, Jesus then gives him an answer, verse 17, look again in your Bibles, verse 17,

09:13.474 --> 09:18.901
Jesus says, but if you wanna enter into life, keep the commandments and the guy says in verse 18, which ones?

09:20.223 --> 09:25.570
And then Jesus is gonna rattle off some of the 10 commandments.

09:25.731 --> 09:31.538
Starting in the middle of verse 18, Jesus said, well, let's start with this, when you shall not murder, that's commandment number six.

09:32.980 --> 09:35.804
You shall not commit adultery, that's commandment number seven.

09:36.786 --> 09:38.949
You shall not steal, that's number eight.

09:39.830 --> 09:42.994
You shall not bear false witness, that's number nine.

09:43.746 --> 09:45.210
Honor your father and mother.

09:45.250 --> 09:46.413
That's number five.

09:47.856 --> 09:51.065
And Jesus says, you shall love your neighbor as yourself.

09:51.165 --> 09:53.330
Now that's not actually one of the Ten Commandments.

09:53.350 --> 09:55.215
He's quoting Leviticus 1918.

09:56.238 --> 09:57.842
Leviticus 1918 says that.

09:58.002 --> 09:59.506
Love your neighbor as yourself.

09:59.554 --> 10:04.980
But in quoting Leviticus 1918, what Jesus is doing is he's summarizing the 10th commandment.

10:05.241 --> 10:08.745
The 10th commandment is not coveting your neighbor or anything that your neighbor has.

10:09.225 --> 10:16.333
And so basically when Jesus quotes Leviticus 1918, he's saying, if you love your neighbors, you love yourself, you're not going to defraud your neighbor.

10:16.353 --> 10:21.419
You're not going to covet your neighbor or anything that your neighbor has because you're going to love your neighbor as yourself.

10:21.479 --> 10:24.262
So he's in essence summarizing the 10th commandment.

10:24.282 --> 10:27.506
And what we have here are six out of the 10 commandments.

10:28.162 --> 10:30.506
And Jesus says to this guy, all right, here's the list.

10:30.546 --> 10:33.711
Don't murder, don't commit adultery, don't steal, don't bear false witness on your father.

10:33.791 --> 10:35.233
Mother, love your neighbor as yourself.

10:35.273 --> 10:36.135
How are you doing there?

10:36.575 --> 10:41.403
And he says, the man says in verse 20, all these things I've kept from my youth.

10:42.324 --> 10:43.626
Now he's a young guy.

10:44.368 --> 10:47.613
So he says, he's already young and he says, I've kept all these from my youth.

10:47.633 --> 10:49.215
There's not much of a gap there, right?

10:49.656 --> 10:55.986
If you're already young and you say, I've kept these since I was a youth, you just haven't lived long enough kid to break these.

10:56.386 --> 10:57.347
That's the reality.

10:57.708 --> 11:04.298
But at the least, he's saying up until this point in my life, Jesus, I have kept these commandments.

11:04.318 --> 11:13.631
Now, Matthew does not record Jesus' reaction, but when Mark tells this story in Mark 10, 21, it records Jesus' reaction.

11:13.892 --> 11:22.545
When the guy says, all of these eyes kept, I have kept from my youth, in Mark 10, 21, it says, Jesus looked at him and loved him.

11:22.565 --> 11:23.506
And I loved that.

11:23.618 --> 11:24.679
I love that verse.

11:24.779 --> 11:31.948
I love that reflection of the Lord because, you know, sometimes we think that God is all about shaming us for what we're not doing right.

11:33.049 --> 11:36.573
And what we need to see about our Lord is that He loves us for what we're doing well.

11:37.634 --> 11:39.676
And He appreciates what we do well.

11:39.917 --> 11:50.549
Now He challenges us about what we're not doing well as He's going to challenge this guy, but He doesn't shame us or disown us in the places that we fall short.

11:50.649 --> 11:51.570
He loves us.

11:52.354 --> 11:53.515
and then he challenges us.

11:54.377 --> 11:55.838
And this is what he does with this guy.

11:57.180 --> 12:04.089
And so when Jesus points out several of the 10 commandments here, this guy basically says, I've checked all the boxes.

12:04.249 --> 12:06.172
Yep, done all these things.

12:06.752 --> 12:08.234
And so it's commendable.

12:08.374 --> 12:12.199
He is seeking eternal life and he's doing a lot of things well.

12:13.221 --> 12:20.530
But here's where it breaks down for this guy and why in the end we read in verse 22 that he walked away sorrowful.

12:21.378 --> 12:24.922
He does not respond to Jesus the way that we hope that he would.

12:25.303 --> 12:26.865
He represents a lot of people.

12:26.905 --> 12:30.489
He's going to end up leaving and walking away sorrowful.

12:31.090 --> 12:31.851
And so why?

12:32.692 --> 12:35.515
Well, listen, here's where it breaks down for this guy.

12:35.916 --> 12:40.201
Since he's doing well in a lot of these areas, six out of 10 commandments.

12:40.241 --> 12:41.943
Yes, Lord, check, check, check, check, check.

12:42.043 --> 12:43.205
I'm doing well in these areas.

12:43.605 --> 12:47.730
He begins to think of himself as being a good person.

12:48.322 --> 13:03.286
If you do a lot of good things well, you begin to think of yourself as a good person, and he translates that, he thinks, I'm basically a good person, so therefore I need to do something good also in order to have eternal life, in order to go to heaven.

13:03.366 --> 13:04.447
That's his theology.

13:04.868 --> 13:10.036
Everything with this guy is about being good or doing good, being good or doing good.

13:10.136 --> 13:11.058
That's the emphasis.

13:11.478 --> 13:16.306
Look again just at the question they asked Jesus in verse 16, good teacher.

13:16.898 --> 13:22.746
What good thing shall I do that I may have eternal life?"

13:23.687 --> 13:25.650
He's basically saying, like, Jesus, you're good.

13:26.030 --> 13:26.451
I'm good.

13:26.651 --> 13:27.292
We're all good.

13:27.432 --> 13:30.897
So what good thing do I need to do to get to heaven, to have eternal life?

13:32.519 --> 13:44.114
Dr. George Barna and the Cultural Research Center at Arizona Christian University found that most Americans, seven out of 10, or 69% of Americans,

13:44.290 --> 13:47.553
believe that mankind is basically good.

13:49.135 --> 13:54.100
Seven in 10 Americans believe that mankind is basically good.

13:54.160 --> 13:55.221
That's not what the Bible says.

13:56.222 --> 13:58.964
But that's what the majority of Americans believe.

13:58.984 --> 14:08.734
And this guy in the story represents millions of people around the world who see themselves, A, as basically good, and B, who believe that they have to do good things in order to get to heaven.

14:09.094 --> 14:12.978
This guy here is a microcosm of the rest of the population of the world.

14:13.634 --> 14:15.857
trying to be a good person, trying to do good things.

14:16.278 --> 14:19.542
What do I need to do that's good in order to have eternal life and to get to heaven?

14:19.562 --> 14:21.825
And there's two problems with that belief system.

14:22.205 --> 14:23.487
The first one is this.

14:23.908 --> 14:25.510
No one is good except God.

14:26.832 --> 14:28.013
Everybody needs to get this.

14:28.634 --> 14:31.318
No one is good except God.

14:32.079 --> 14:35.203
Now, I grew up listening to Linda Ronstadt.

14:35.223 --> 14:37.206
How many of you grew up listening to Linda Ronstadt?

14:37.566 --> 14:39.008
Oh, not very many of you.

14:39.228 --> 14:42.212
You're afraid to raise your hands because then we all know that you did drugs.

14:42.292 --> 14:43.474
But anyway,

14:44.002 --> 14:52.273
I grew up listening to Linda Ronstadt, and I didn't need the Bible to understand that you're no good, you're no good, you're no good baby, you're no good.

14:53.475 --> 14:56.900
I'm gonna say it again, you're no good, anyway.

14:58.602 --> 15:00.845
I digress, but I didn't need the Bible.

15:00.966 --> 15:02.948
I understood about the human nature.

15:03.008 --> 15:04.310
We're no good in essence.

15:04.330 --> 15:07.995
And if you didn't listen to Linda Ronstadt, let me tell you what the Bible says.

15:08.055 --> 15:09.938
Listen to this, Romans 7, 18.

15:10.242 --> 15:15.791
For I know that in me, Paul says, that is in my flesh, nothing good dwells, nothing good.

15:17.474 --> 15:19.838
But my mommy told me that I'm one of a kind.

15:21.380 --> 15:29.653
Well, I hate to melt your dreams, snowflake, but you're no different than anybody else in regards to human nature.

15:30.174 --> 15:35.423
The Bible says in Romans 3, 10, there is no one righteous, not even one.

15:36.384 --> 15:37.426
Every single one of us.

15:37.890 --> 15:38.971
guilty before God.

15:39.012 --> 15:42.136
Romans 3, 23, for all of sin and full short of the glory of God.

15:42.176 --> 15:44.879
None of us measures up to the perfect standard of God.

15:44.980 --> 15:50.928
Ecclesiastes 7, 20, for there is not a just man on earth who does good and does not sin.

15:51.929 --> 15:54.573
So we gotta stop talking about how good people are.

15:54.733 --> 15:57.176
People aren't good, not intrinsically, not the human nature.

15:57.877 --> 16:00.721
Good is a very relative term and it can be used for a lot of things.

16:00.781 --> 16:04.466
You can say, good morning, good night, good idea.

16:04.610 --> 16:15.966
good food, good times, good game, good job, good humor, good grief, good and plenty, but don't say people are good because the human nature is not.

16:16.867 --> 16:17.748
And here's the problem.

16:17.848 --> 16:25.779
If we believe the narrative that I am basically good, then I will not see my need for God because only God is good.

16:27.181 --> 16:27.742
Did you hear that?

16:29.064 --> 16:33.810
If I believe, if anybody believes the lie, the narrative, that I am basically good,

16:34.306 --> 16:39.354
then we will not see our need for God because only God is good.

16:41.137 --> 16:49.991
The other fallacy of this guy in our story, which is similar to what a lot of people think today too, is that he has to do good things.

16:50.111 --> 16:53.496
Not only does he think of himself as being good, but nobody's good except God.

16:54.538 --> 16:58.163
But then he also thinks I have to do good things in order to gain eternal life.

16:58.243 --> 17:02.450
Again, in his question, verse 16, good teacher, what good thing

17:02.658 --> 17:04.801
Shall I do that I may have eternal life?"

17:05.282 --> 17:08.967
The second important point here is that doing good things won't get us to heaven.

17:10.069 --> 17:15.497
A lot of people think that doing good things does get us to heaven, but it isn't true.

17:16.519 --> 17:22.067
Now it's natural for this guy to think that he has to do something good to get to heaven because he's rich, young, and successful.

17:22.468 --> 17:29.458
He is used to working hard and doing a lot of things and then having a good result at the end of that day.

17:30.178 --> 17:32.214
And so he translates that into his theology.

17:32.597 --> 17:35.922
If you work hard and apply yourself, you'll be successful.

17:36.002 --> 17:39.745
So now he thinks, if I work hard and apply myself, I'm going to be able to go to heaven.

17:40.126 --> 17:41.627
What's the good thing I have to do?

17:41.667 --> 17:43.368
He just didn't know which was the good thing.

17:43.669 --> 17:47.952
But all along, he's applying his work ethic, which is noble, it's admirable.

17:47.992 --> 17:48.953
We should all work hard.

17:48.993 --> 17:51.255
We should all do well.

17:51.976 --> 18:01.764
But he's thinking that that translates into my access to heaven, that if I work hard and do a lot of good things, then I'm going to be able to go to heaven.

18:02.105 --> 18:03.886
And he's relying on his own ability.

18:03.906 --> 18:05.988
He's relying on his own efforts.

18:05.968 --> 18:07.450
on his own hard work.

18:07.510 --> 18:12.998
That's the formula that he's always followed, so naturally he assumes that's how heaven works too.

18:13.799 --> 18:21.010
But eternal life is one thing that Jesus is going to let this guy know he can't work to get and he can't pay to get.

18:21.290 --> 18:25.657
Jesus did all the work for us on the cross, right?

18:26.758 --> 18:29.562
Jesus did all the work for us on the cross.

18:30.704 --> 18:34.930
Now listen, the fact that I don't have to do any good works

18:35.362 --> 18:42.249
in order to be able to get to heaven or somehow get on God's good side should be liberating to us.

18:42.969 --> 18:48.555
That should be freeing to us because it means you don't have to perform to get to God.

18:49.256 --> 18:50.156
That's what that means.

18:50.837 --> 18:54.361
Here's the difference between all of the world religions and Christianity.

18:55.221 --> 19:00.967
All of the world religions basically teach that it's about man's effort to reach God.

19:02.048 --> 19:04.050
That's really what all world religions teach.

19:04.322 --> 19:06.486
Man's effort, what do you have to do?

19:06.766 --> 19:07.828
How do you have to perform?

19:08.168 --> 19:09.110
How do you have to behave?

19:09.210 --> 19:11.754
What works do you have to accomplish in order to reach God?

19:13.097 --> 19:14.058
Christianity is different.

19:15.000 --> 19:18.526
In that, it's about a relationship and it's inverted.

19:19.047 --> 19:23.474
It's not man's effort in trying to reach God, it's what God went to to reach man.

19:24.322 --> 19:25.984
God condescended to our level.

19:26.024 --> 19:27.325
That's what Christianity teaches.

19:27.365 --> 19:32.951
That's why this is a relationship and that's why it's not based on my performance or my effort or my work.

19:32.991 --> 19:34.854
It's based on what God has done for me.

19:35.214 --> 19:38.918
Christianity is not a performance-based religion.

19:39.278 --> 19:42.162
It is a grace-based relationship.

19:42.842 --> 19:46.066
It is not based on my performance about what I do.

19:46.206 --> 19:51.292
It is based on the grace of what Jesus has already done on the cross for me.

19:52.112 --> 19:53.554
And it's a big distinction.

19:53.858 --> 19:58.164
between what Christianity offers and what all other world religions offer.

19:58.204 --> 20:01.549
And what that means for us is staggering.

20:02.470 --> 20:05.915
It's not dependent upon me to do something.

20:06.736 --> 20:09.761
I just have to respond to what was already done for me.

20:10.361 --> 20:12.625
This is why Jesus said on the cross, it is finished.

20:13.566 --> 20:16.370
It is finished because he accomplished that work for us.

20:16.674 --> 20:20.340
But we come with our performance oriented mindset and we think, well, I can't be finished.

20:20.360 --> 20:23.405
There's gotta be some stuff I've gotta do to contribute to this whole formula.

20:23.745 --> 20:24.767
Well, that isn't true.

20:25.147 --> 20:35.604
But if you think that, if you think that you have to be a good person and do good things in order to gain God's favor or in order to go to heaven, then my question for you is if you believe that, how good is good enough?

20:37.507 --> 20:38.348
How good is good enough?

20:38.368 --> 20:42.695
If you really think that, if you think, well, if I'm just a good person and I do good things, then I'll get to heaven.

20:43.056 --> 20:44.658
How good is good enough?

20:45.442 --> 20:49.627
What kind of confidence do you have in that system if you believe that?

20:50.988 --> 20:54.472
What kind of confidence do you have that you'll ever make at the heaven based on your goodness?

20:54.873 --> 20:56.194
I mean, does God grade on the curve?

20:57.436 --> 20:58.897
Do you think God grades on the curve?

20:58.917 --> 21:03.443
Do you think God's gonna throw out the lowest grades and just kind of equal the playing field in the class?

21:04.284 --> 21:11.332
Do you think that God's like some traffic cop on a good day that you broke the law, but he's gonna just give you a pass anyway?

21:11.852 --> 21:13.394
That's not how it works.

21:13.762 --> 21:15.606
Does God have a big scale in heaven?

21:16.448 --> 21:23.885
And hopefully you're thinking if you believe that kind of philosophy that your good deeds outweigh your bad deeds and then God's going to let you in?

21:23.945 --> 21:29.778
Because I don't know what your scale looks like, but mine kind of tips the other way, doesn't yours?

21:29.890 --> 21:36.139
You really think you're confident enough in all of your goodness that somehow that's gonna tip the scale in your favor?

21:36.359 --> 21:37.961
Well, God doesn't operate that way.

21:38.181 --> 21:40.124
He doesn't have some grand scale in heaven.

21:40.425 --> 21:41.726
He doesn't great on the curve.

21:42.167 --> 21:45.071
He doesn't try to level the playing field in that sense.

21:45.812 --> 21:53.983
That philosophy of how I gain access to heaven by being a good person and doing good works gives me zero confidence.

21:54.444 --> 21:58.930
I don't know, anybody can trust that if you have an ounce of honesty

21:59.074 --> 22:00.015
about yourself.

22:00.977 --> 22:10.250
So then, if you are honest about yourself and you realize your own good works won't get you there and you're not good enough to get there on your own, what is the answer?

22:10.811 --> 22:18.602
When this guy asks Jesus the question in verse 16, good teacher, what good thing must I do in order to have eternal life?

22:20.024 --> 22:23.248
Notice Jesus' answer in verse 17.

22:24.791 --> 22:27.154
Jesus said to him, why do you call me good?

22:28.386 --> 22:33.612
No one is good, but one that is God."

22:33.632 --> 22:34.453
Now, it's very interesting.

22:34.533 --> 22:37.736
Notice here how Jesus answers the question with a question.

22:38.977 --> 22:43.062
The guy asks, what good thing must I do to have eternal life?

22:43.122 --> 22:44.664
Jesus answers, why do you call me good?

22:44.924 --> 22:50.810
He answers a question with a question because he's trying to draw out this guy's worldview.

22:50.970 --> 22:57.938
Everybody comes at life from their personal perspective and their own worldview that gets shaped by different factors.

22:58.018 --> 23:03.063
So to answer a question with a question is actually a very good communication tool so you can understand.

23:03.564 --> 23:09.290
Help me understand where you're coming from and what certain words mean before I just blurred out an answer.

23:09.330 --> 23:12.634
And so Jesus is drawing out from this guy, his worldview.

23:12.654 --> 23:16.438
And here's the reason why he's asking this question of this young man.

23:16.958 --> 23:19.040
Because he says to him, why do you call me good?

23:19.100 --> 23:20.302
No one is good except God.

23:20.342 --> 23:24.306
In other words, are you calling me good because you believe that I'm God?

23:25.730 --> 23:29.575
And if you believe I'm God, are you willing to do what I'm about to tell you?

23:31.377 --> 23:40.147
See, he's establishing and revealing the guy's worldview because if the guy believes that he's God and that's why he's calling him good, now he's accountable.

23:40.968 --> 23:41.890
Are you going to do what I say?

23:41.910 --> 23:44.052
If you call me good, then you must think I'm God.

23:44.072 --> 23:46.916
If you think I'm God, are you about to obey what I'm about to tell you?

23:47.937 --> 23:50.941
And so he's challenging this guy with a question to draw out his worldview.

23:53.143 --> 23:55.506
He's trying to awaken this man's consciousness.

23:56.258 --> 23:59.003
that he is in fact God, that Jesus is God.

24:00.405 --> 24:04.152
And basically, again, Jesus is saying, if you call me good, then you're calling me God.

24:04.172 --> 24:07.919
And if you're calling me God, are you going to do what I tell you to do?

24:09.161 --> 24:20.882
Now, in the follow up to what Jesus now is going to tell him, Jesus says something that if I were to say, you all would think this is heresy.

24:21.378 --> 24:28.826
And the reason is because Jesus points to some of the 10 commandments as the answer to the question of eternal life.

24:29.066 --> 24:33.912
If you just obey some of the 10 commandments here, notice, I'll explain, but notice what Jesus does here again.

24:34.472 --> 24:40.639
Between verses 17, 18, and 19, he draws this guy's attention to six out of the 10 commandments.

24:41.860 --> 24:42.601
What about all these?

24:43.242 --> 24:47.346
If you do all these, then you'll have life.

24:47.426 --> 24:51.012
If somebody ever came up to me and said, what must I do to have eternal life?

24:51.052 --> 24:53.616
And you overheard a conversation and I said, you know what?

24:53.636 --> 24:55.679
Just obey the 10 commandments and you're good to go.

24:55.960 --> 24:58.063
You'd be looking at me like, why don't you tell him about Jesus?

24:58.804 --> 25:00.567
Why don't you tell him to believe in Jesus?

25:00.627 --> 25:02.390
Why are you throwing out the 10 commandment thing?

25:02.771 --> 25:05.275
Okay, listen, there's a reason why Jesus does this.

25:05.856 --> 25:11.845
But you should wonder, why doesn't he just simply say believe in me and you'll have eternal life?

25:12.366 --> 25:14.770
That was the scene in Acts chapter 16.

25:14.914 --> 25:22.286
In Acts chapter 16, Paul and Silas are thrown in prison, unjustifiably so, but they're thrown in prison preaching the gospel.

25:22.346 --> 25:30.940
There's a Roman soldier there of the Philippian jailer, and God brings about an earthquake to open up the prison doors.

25:31.080 --> 25:32.082
Paul and Silas

25:32.194 --> 25:45.076
Paul and Silas are able to leave the Philippian jailer being a Roman officer knows if the criminals escape under my watch, the Roman government will impose their penalty on me, so he's about ready to take his own life.

25:46.037 --> 25:48.561
And Paul and Silas don't do that, don't do that, don't do that.

25:49.223 --> 25:54.632
And the Philippian jailer looks at Paul and Silas and asks a very similar question to what this guy's asking.

25:54.652 --> 25:58.418
He asks of Paul and Silas, what must I do to be saved?

25:58.722 --> 26:00.765
Very similar, this guy's like, what must I do?

26:00.825 --> 26:02.167
What good thing to have eternal life?

26:02.848 --> 26:10.098
And Paul and Silas respond, they're in Acts 16 and they say, believe on the Lord Jesus Christ and you shall be saved, you and your household.

26:10.118 --> 26:11.920
Now why didn't Jesus say something like that?

26:11.940 --> 26:13.542
Just believe in me and you're good to go.

26:13.963 --> 26:17.668
Why does he speak here about some of these 10 commandments?

26:17.948 --> 26:18.609
Here's the reason.

26:20.011 --> 26:27.922
Because Jesus is about to show the guy that obeying the commandments won't save a person.

26:28.866 --> 26:41.483
You see, as much as this guy was good about obeying some of the commandments, Jesus was about to expose the guy's inability to obey all of the commandments.

26:42.004 --> 26:54.081
And if you can't obey all of the commandments, it shows that you're not that good after all, and if you're not that good after all, what's your hope of ever getting to heaven other than a savior?

26:55.643 --> 26:58.066
So he wants to expose this guy's false theology.

26:58.594 --> 26:59.956
You think you're good, you're not.

27:00.597 --> 27:02.099
You think you've done a lot of good things.

27:02.680 --> 27:08.949
Let me tell you, let me expose the fact that you're not as good and you don't do as good of things as you think you do.

27:09.329 --> 27:10.431
So here's what Jesus does.

27:11.653 --> 27:19.104
When the 10 commandments were given from God through Moses, they were in two tablets of the testimony, two tablets.

27:20.025 --> 27:26.354
Now a lot of people think the tablets were just evenly divided, five commandments on one tablet, five commandments on the other, they weren't.

27:26.978 --> 27:31.346
They were four commandments on the first tablet, six on the second tablet.

27:31.366 --> 27:37.176
The first tablet of the ten commandments, the first four commandments of the ten commandments are all vertical.

27:38.118 --> 27:40.101
It's all about man's relationship with God.

27:40.842 --> 27:43.347
That's the first four commandments of the ten commandments.

27:43.367 --> 27:49.798
The second tablet was commandments number six through ten, and all those commandments were horizontal.

27:50.459 --> 27:51.922
Man's relationship to each other.

27:53.282 --> 27:57.246
When Jesus is quoting the Ten Commandments, you know which tablet he quotes?

27:58.327 --> 27:59.988
The second one.

28:00.008 --> 28:04.813
He quotes all of the commandments related to man's relationship to man.

28:05.714 --> 28:08.116
And this guy responds positively.

28:08.957 --> 28:11.900
I've kept all those commandments since I was a youth.

28:12.580 --> 28:18.986
And Jesus looked at him and loved him because Jesus knew the guy's problem was not with the second tablet.

28:19.727 --> 28:22.770
The guy's problem was with the first tablet.

28:23.138 --> 28:26.022
Particularly, commandment number one and commandment number two.

28:26.263 --> 28:28.687
Commandment number one, you shall have no other gods before me.

28:28.947 --> 28:31.892
Commandment number two, you shall not make or serve any idols.

28:32.332 --> 28:33.795
You know what this guy's problem was?

28:34.856 --> 28:37.901
He had made money his God and success his idol.

28:40.124 --> 28:43.209
And he was guilty of breaking the commandments.

28:43.990 --> 28:47.215
Jesus starts with the tablet that he knows this guy has done well.

28:47.556 --> 28:48.978
He looks at him and he loves him.

28:49.314 --> 29:00.249
But this is why Jesus then says to him in verse 21 in your Bibles, if you want to be perfect, go sell what you have and give to the poor and you will have treasure in heaven and come follow me.

29:00.629 --> 29:01.631
And he touched a nerve.

29:03.393 --> 29:04.154
He touched a nerve.

29:06.437 --> 29:09.501
He exposed this guy's heart.

29:09.521 --> 29:12.605
He made this guy realize you're doing well on the horizontal.

29:12.786 --> 29:15.650
You're not doing that well on the vertical, are you?

29:15.670 --> 29:18.994
Because money has become your God and success has become your idol.

29:19.586 --> 29:23.153
So when Jesus challenges him about why do you just sell everything you have?

29:23.975 --> 29:26.440
Why don't you pry yourself loose from all your stuff?

29:27.683 --> 29:31.070
Sadly, one of the saddest verses in the Bible is verse 22.

29:31.411 --> 29:36.581
It says, but when the young man heard that saying he went away sorrowful for he had great possessions.

29:38.125 --> 29:38.906
Now listen to me on this.

29:38.946 --> 29:40.690
The issue was not that he was wealthy.

29:41.250 --> 29:45.557
Deuteronomy 8, 18 says that God gives us the ability to produce wealth.

29:45.877 --> 29:47.900
That wasn't the issue, the fact that he was wealthy.

29:48.100 --> 29:55.752
The issue was that money had become his God and success had become his idol in violation of commandments one and commandments number two.

29:57.234 --> 30:01.040
But instead of turning to Jesus and humbling himself and saying, you know what, you're right.

30:02.382 --> 30:06.348
I've been worshiping, honoring and loving and living for other things besides God.

30:06.489 --> 30:10.034
I might be doing well in the horizontal, but my vertical is a little weak here.

30:10.210 --> 30:14.034
instead of humbling himself and saying, so therefore, what do I need?

30:14.074 --> 30:16.036
And Jesus could then say, you need a savior.

30:16.056 --> 30:20.881
He's using the commandments to expose this guy's heart to make him realize you're a lawbreaker.

30:21.122 --> 30:22.623
You're guilty like everybody else.

30:22.904 --> 30:27.489
It's wonderful that you've been obeying commandments six through 10, but you're weak on one through four.

30:27.869 --> 30:34.756
So it's a helpful tool so that the guy would realize, I'm a lawbreaker and I'm guilty like everybody else in the world.

30:34.836 --> 30:35.497
What do I need?

30:35.557 --> 30:36.338
You need a savior.

30:36.994 --> 30:41.600
You're not good enough, and the good things you do do aren't good enough in order to get you to heaven.

30:41.961 --> 30:43.343
So therefore, what do you need?

30:43.503 --> 30:44.284
You need a savior.

30:44.444 --> 30:48.369
And instead of this guy just humbling himself, coming to the place where he says, you're right.

30:49.211 --> 30:53.236
He walks away sorrowful because he had great possessions.

30:54.057 --> 30:56.160
That was his God, those were his idols.

30:57.742 --> 31:06.514
The actor Jim Carrey once said, quote, I think everybody should get rich and famous and do everything they ever dreamed of so they can see it's not the answer, end quote.

31:09.090 --> 31:13.356
I think Jim Carrey is still seeking the answer, but at least I agree with what he says there.

31:14.558 --> 31:16.661
We're all guilty of breaking God's commandments.

31:18.484 --> 31:25.013
There's no answer for our sinful human condition except Jesus.

31:26.655 --> 31:33.245
You don't need to leave here sad today like this young guy left sad after Jesus exposed his heart.

31:33.746 --> 31:34.967
You can humble yourself.

31:35.508 --> 31:36.850
You can come to the place.

31:37.090 --> 31:39.694
where you acknowledge your own need for a Savior too.

31:40.014 --> 31:41.396
Maybe you believed all your life.

31:41.476 --> 31:44.861
It's about being a good person, doing good things, and then you're good to go.

31:45.442 --> 31:47.726
I'm telling you that is not what the Bible teaches.

31:48.447 --> 31:51.291
The Bible teaches that there is none righteous, no not one.

31:51.331 --> 31:54.736
We've all sinned, we've all fallen short of the perfect standard of God.

31:55.657 --> 31:57.119
We're all guilty before God.

31:57.981 --> 32:04.370
But the good news is it's not based on my performance because the relationship with Jesus is not a performance based

32:04.546 --> 32:06.588
a relationship based on what I do.

32:06.728 --> 32:12.555
It's a grace based relationship because of what Jesus has done by dying on a cross.

32:13.716 --> 32:14.998
He paid the price for me.

32:15.138 --> 32:16.579
He took my sins for me.

32:17.761 --> 32:20.964
He took my shame, my guilt, died for my sins.

32:21.465 --> 32:30.855
And then the invitation is if I would just simply believe in Jesus and put my trust in him as my savior for what he has done, that's how you have eternal life.

32:32.077 --> 32:33.138
Your sins forgiven.

32:34.018 --> 32:40.929
knowing that you're going to heaven because of your faith in Jesus Christ is the only Savior given a demand by which we must be saved.

32:42.111 --> 32:46.758
And so none of us is good enough, and none of us can do enough good things.

32:47.719 --> 32:52.066
But Jesus has done the supreme thing by dying it across for our sins.

32:52.427 --> 32:54.430
Do you know Him?

32:54.450 --> 32:57.775
You might be part of that 82% that thinks, I'm going to end up there one day.

32:58.035 --> 32:59.858
Well, do you know that for sure?

33:00.930 --> 33:02.071
Or maybe you're part of the 2%.

33:02.351 --> 33:03.693
I don't think I have any chance.

33:03.933 --> 33:07.796
Yeah, there's absolutely a chance for every person.

33:08.217 --> 33:12.661
You just have to humble yourself and believe in Jesus as your Lord and Savior.

33:13.862 --> 33:14.583
Let's pray together.

33:15.244 --> 33:17.546
I'm going to give you that invitation to trust Him right now.

33:18.667 --> 33:27.195
Whether you're here in the sanctuary watching online or listening to this later by podcast, if you don't know Christ as your Savior, I want to invite you today, open up your heart to Him.

33:29.037 --> 33:30.578
You might be a decent person.

33:31.522 --> 33:34.606
You've tried all your life to do good things, but it's not good enough.

33:35.948 --> 33:38.272
Or you might know about yourself, I'm not good at all.

33:38.993 --> 33:39.533
That's okay.

33:39.554 --> 33:41.476
Jesus died for every person.

33:42.798 --> 33:44.420
There's none righteous, not one.

33:46.343 --> 33:48.526
So Father, we humbled ourselves before you right now.

33:48.586 --> 33:50.930
We're thankful that you died in a cross for our sins.

33:52.612 --> 33:53.874
We can't improve upon it.

33:53.914 --> 33:55.356
We can't work our way to heaven.

33:55.376 --> 33:59.442
And none of us is good enough, but you alone are good because you're God.

34:00.386 --> 34:05.251
and you sent your son Jesus to die in a cross, to do for us what we cannot do for ourselves.

34:06.392 --> 34:08.173
We might have a relationship with you.

34:09.435 --> 34:14.019
More than religion, this is a relationship based on what you've done for us.

34:15.921 --> 34:25.209
So Lord, I pray right now for every man, woman, and young person who hears this study together and is at a place where they recognize their need for you today.

34:27.491 --> 34:30.194
Maybe all their lives, they've thought that it's based on

34:30.306 --> 34:35.272
the good things that they do, but today I pray they would realize it's the good thing that you've already done.

34:37.315 --> 34:41.560
That they would put their faith and trust in you as Lord and Savior.

34:43.502 --> 34:46.546
So I'm going to pause in my prayer with your head still bowed, your eyes closed.

34:46.586 --> 34:50.852
If you want to trust Christ as your Savior, I'm going to lead in a word of prayer right now.

34:51.132 --> 34:52.674
And you can jump in on this prayer.

34:52.994 --> 34:54.096
You can pray it with me.

34:54.116 --> 34:54.997
I'll go slowly.

34:55.698 --> 34:59.122
So right where you're seated, you can just whisper this prayer, make it yours.

34:59.650 --> 35:00.892
Receive Christ today.

35:00.932 --> 35:02.474
Trust Him as your Lord and Savior.

35:02.734 --> 35:04.376
You want to know how to have eternal life?

35:04.677 --> 35:08.182
Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and you shall be saved.

35:08.903 --> 35:09.904
He's our only answer.

35:11.005 --> 35:12.928
There are not multiple paths to get to God.

35:12.948 --> 35:13.669
There's only one.

35:14.831 --> 35:17.334
Jesus said, I am the way, the truth, the life.

35:17.394 --> 35:19.397
No man comes to the Father except by me.

35:20.859 --> 35:23.122
So if you want to pray this prayer, just pray it with me.

35:23.714 --> 35:24.615
Make it yours, too.

35:24.655 --> 35:25.737
Just say, Lord Jesus.

35:25.957 --> 35:28.060
Just whisper it, right to the Lord.

35:28.080 --> 35:29.302
You just pray it right where you are.

35:29.342 --> 35:30.343
Just say, Lord Jesus.

35:32.086 --> 35:34.509
I thank you that you died in a cross for my sins.

35:37.293 --> 35:38.996
I understand that I'm not a good person.

35:39.076 --> 35:39.757
Nobody is.

35:41.900 --> 35:43.522
But you did a good thing for me.

35:45.505 --> 35:47.628
By dying in a cross for my sins.

35:49.911 --> 35:52.114
So I confess my need for you today.

35:53.954 --> 36:02.905
I ask you, Lord, to forgive me of my sins, to come into my heart and my life, to be my Lord and Savior.

36:05.268 --> 36:10.934
I trust you today by faith in your finished work on the cross.

36:12.797 --> 36:13.998
Thank you for loving me.

36:15.580 --> 36:17.703
Thank you for dying for me.

36:19.164 --> 36:20.486
Thank you for saving me.

36:22.749 --> 36:23.890
In your name, I pray.

36:25.282 --> 36:26.525
and all God's people said.

36:26.945 --> 36:27.286
Amen.

36:27.927 --> 36:34.761
If you prayed that prayer with me a moment ago, there's going to be a pastor down front here to hand out Bibles just so you can remember today's decision.

36:35.483 --> 36:36.746
We praise God for you.

36:36.786 --> 36:39.291
Let's give God praise for his infinite love for us.

36:39.952 --> 36:40.313
Amen.

36:40.493 --> 36:41.135
Thank you, Lord.

36:43.119 --> 36:43.980
God bless you all.

36:44.662 --> 36:45.363
Have a great day.

36:45.403 --> 36:45.985
You're dismissed.

36:46.005 --> 36:46.706
Have a great day.

